  <main class="section-main">
    <h1 class="main-title">About PHP</h1>
    <p>
      PHP (Hypertext Preprocessor) is a widely used server-side scripting language that is primarily designed for web development. It is a versatile and powerful language known for its simplicity and ease of use. PHP is embedded within HTML code and executed on the server, generating dynamic web pages.

      One of the key advantages of PHP is its broad compatibility across different operating systems and web servers. It supports various databases, such as MySQL, PostgreSQL, and Oracle, allowing developers to interact with databases and handle data effectively. PHP also provides extensive support for different protocols, including HTTP, FTP, and SMTP, enabling the development of robust web applications.

      PHP's syntax is similar to C, Java, and Perl, making it accessible to developers familiar with these languages. It offers a wide range of functionalities and features for web development, such as file manipulation, form handling, session management, and encryption. It also has built-in support for processing XML and JSON data.

      The PHP community is vast and active, contributing to its continuous improvement and extensive documentation. There are numerous frameworks and libraries available, like Laravel, Symfony, and CodeIgniter, which aid in rapid application development and promote code reusability.

      Over the years, PHP has evolved significantly, addressing security concerns and enhancing performance. The latest versions of PHP include features like scalar type declarations, return type declarations, and anonymous classes, bringing modern programming concepts to the language.

      With its widespread usage and mature ecosystem, PHP remains a popular choice for web development, powering countless websites and web applications. Its flexibility, versatility, and large developer community contribute to its ongoing relevance and continued growth in the industry.
    </p>
